                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">2. Residency & Presence</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-500">Does the manager need to live in California?</p>
                </div>
                <div class="flex space-x-2">
                    <div class="px-4 py-2 bg-stone-100 rounded-lg text-xs font-bold text-slate-600">ON-SITE MANDATORY</div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3">
                <div class="p-8 border-r border-stone-100 space-y-4">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800">Physical Presence</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                        The manager must be <strong>stationed at the licensed location</strong> during all business hours. You cannot have one manager "overseeing" multiple branches from another state.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="p-8 border-r border-stone-100 space-y-4">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800">CA Nexus</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                        While the law doesn't technically say "must have a CA driver's license," the DFPI background check (Statement of Identity) requires a residency history. Living in CA is the practical standard.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="p-8 space-y-4">
                    <h4 class="font-bold text-amber-800">Remote Work?</h4>
                    <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
                        Post-COVID, the DFPI has allowed <em>some</em> flexibility for staff, but the <strong>Qualified Manager</strong> is generally expected to be physically tethered to the main office for audit purposes.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- SECTION 3: OUT OF STATE EXPERIENCE -->
        <section class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
